ğŸ”¶ What is VTP (VLAN Trunking Protocol)?

VTP is a Cisco proprietary protocol used to manage VLANs across multiple switches automatically.

It allows you to:

âœ” Create VLANs on one switch
âœ” Automatically send those VLANs to all other switches in the network
âœ” Keep VLAN names and IDs consistent

ğŸ“Œ VTP is used only between switches connected using trunk ports.

ğŸ”¶ Why VTP Is Used?

Without VTP â†’ You must manually create VLANs on every switch.

With VTP â†’ You create VLANs only once (on the server switch), and they automatically propagate.

âœ” Saves time
âœ” Prevents mistakes
âœ” Ensures consistency

ğŸ”¶ VTP Modes

There are three main modes:

Mode	Purpose
Server	Can create/modify/delete VLANs â†’ distributes to all switches
Client	Cannot create VLANs â†’ only receives VLAN info
Transparent	Does NOT participate in VTP but forwards VTP packets
ğŸ”¶ VTP Domain

All switches must be in the same VTP domain name to participate.

Example:

vtp domain BOB-Network

ğŸ”¶ VTP Version

VTP has 3 versions:

Version	Use
V1	Basic VLAN propagation
V2	Token Ring support (old)
V3	Supports extended VLANs (1006â€“4096), more secure

Best practice: Use VTP Version 3.

ğŸ”¶ How VTP Works (Simple)

1ï¸âƒ£ Switch in server mode creates a VLAN
2ï¸âƒ£ VLAN information is carried over trunk ports
3ï¸âƒ£ Other switches in client mode automatically learn VLANs
4ï¸âƒ£ All switches stay synchronized

ğŸ”¶ VTP Pruning

VTP pruning reduces unnecessary VLAN traffic on trunks.

Example:
âœ” If VLAN 30 does not exist on Switch-2
âœ” Trunk will stop sending VLAN 30 broadcast/multicast traffic to Switch-2

Command:

vtp pruning

ğŸ”¶ VTP Configuration Example (Cisco Switch)
Set VTP Domain Name
vtp domain BOB-Network

Set VTP Mode
vtp mode server


(or client / transparent)

Set VTP Version
vtp version 3

Enable VTP Pruning
vtp pruning


Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) is a network protocol used in Layer 2 (switching) to prevent loops in a network that has redundant links.

ğŸ•¸ï¸ Why do we need STP?

In a network with multiple switches, redundant links are used for backup.
But Layer 2 doesnâ€™t have TTL (Time To Live) like IP, so a broadcast frame can loop endlessly, causing:

Broadcast storms

MAC address table instability

Network crash

ğŸ‘‰ STP automatically detects loops and blocks extra paths, keeping only one active path.

ğŸ”§ How STP Works (Simple Explanation)
1ï¸âƒ£ Elect Root Bridge

All switches choose one as the Root Bridge (center of the network).
Lowest Bridge ID (Priority + MAC) wins.

2ï¸âƒ£ Calculate Best Path

Each switch calculates the best path to the Root Bridge using STP messages (BPDUs).

3ï¸âƒ£ Block Redundant Links

To prevent loops, STP blocks ports that would create a loop.

ğŸ“¦ Port Roles in STP
Port Role	Function
Root Port (RP)	Best path to Root Bridge
Designated Port (DP)	Forwarding port for a network segment
Blocked / Non-Designated Port	Prevents loops

spanning-tree mode rapid-pvst
spanning-tree extend system-id
spanning-tree vlan 1-4094 priority 4096

NTP 
Network Time Protocol
It is used to synchronize time between computers, servers, switches, routers, and network devices over a network.
How to configure NTP
configure terminal
clock timezone IST 5 30
ntp server 10.10.10.10
ntp server 10.10.10.11
end
 â€œNTP has been configured on all network devices using internal authenticated NTP servers to ensure accurate system time, reliable log correlation, and compliance with RBI security guidelines.â€
